vulnerability to highlight the inner emotional lives of Black men. In focusing on vulnerability these satirists attend to America’s most basic assumptions about Black men. Contemporary Black satire is a highly visible and celebrated site of black masculine self-expression. Black satirists leverage this visibility to trouble discourses on race and gender in the Post-Civil Rights era. More specifically, contemporary Black satire uses laughter to decenter Black men from the socio-political tradition of the Race Man.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAfrican Americans in the performing arts. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aAmerican fictionxAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aSatire, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  arace, 21st century, Satire, black humorists, blackface, Bert Williams, Uncle Julius, Conjure Tales, 20th Century, black, black men, America, United States, black satire, black masculine interiority, black masculine, Post-Civil Rights Era, community building, catharsis, vulnerability, blackness, masculinity, African American literary, African American, Black satirists, Barack Obama, Obama, Kendrick Lamar, Key and Peele.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2022z9783110992809oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishz978311099281608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076647940uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197882428740uhttps: